# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __iter__, __next__, __len__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __iter__: false for all 10 — iter(x) protocol not in own __dict__.
# __next__: false for all 10 — next(x) protocol not in own __dict__.
# __len__:  false for all 10 — len(x) protocol not in own __dict__.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. The iterator and sizing protocol dunders (__iter__, __next__,
#   __len__) are not overridden in the Python-level __dict__ of any of the
#   10 types.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue note: although these types store items
#   in an internal data structure, access is mediated exclusively through
#   get()/put() coroutines and qsize()/empty()/full() methods. None of the
#   three queue types define __iter__, __next__, or __len__ in their own __dict__.
# asyncio.Future note: Future manages a state machine (PENDING/RUNNING/
#   CANCELLED/FINISHED) and a result slot, but the result is retrieved via
#   result() — not via iteration or len(). None of __iter__, __next__, or
#   __len__ is defined in Future.__dict__.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a boolean flag via set()/clear()/is_set();
#   even though it has a logical boolean state, none of __iter__, __next__,
#   or __len__ is defined in asyncio.Event.__dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   behind acquire()/release() coroutines; no iterator or sizing protocol dunders
#   are defined in their __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

